    "Narration:"
    "You watch as the work you gave away is repackaged. Investors rename apprentices 'service cohorts' and set quotas. A small-town contract you read aloud in a meeting redefines 'volunteer' into 'retainer' and 'community benefits' into 'service credits.' The words are technical; their edges are designed to be painless."
    "Rafi's byline moves from praise to critique. His new piece lays out what you already suspected and what you did not want to see: appropriation of open methods, labor extraction disguised as opportunity, the fiscalization of"
    "care. The article is tender and merciless, and you read it in the dark while the kettle clicks."
    show rafi_soto at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_soto "I had to tell it straight.' (He looks at you. There is no triumph in his voice; only regret.) 'People are being tied into rolling contracts. It’s not what we meant."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "I know."

    rafi_soto "Are you—are you okay? Did it—did it feel like victory to you?"
    "Maya Kestrel [Thought]: I measure victory not by headlines but by who still eats from the harbor tomorrow. The answer is a silence that fills the room like fog."

    maya_kestrel "For a while it did.' (You let yourself say the truth.) 'Then I saw what the openness became."
    "Narration:"

    "You close your notebook. In the margins, beneath a sketch of eelgrass root structures, memos proliferate" "Branding partnership,' 'pilot rights reserved,' 'replication fee."
    # [Scene: High Tide Boardwalk | Twilight]
    hide rafi_soto
    hide maya_kestrel

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The sea, ever patient; the faint rustle of a brochure left on a bench]
    # [Smell: Cold salt wind, the metallic tang of plans made in rooms far from wood smoke]
    "Narration:"
    "You walk alone along the boardwalk. Brochures drift across the planks like dead leaves. Somewhere, a vendor plays the same recorded voice that once sounded like a promise. Ilias Navarro's last suitcase sits by the bench where he and you once planned nocturnal seedings; his plane leaves at dawn."
    "You stop at the plaque and trace the engraved letters with a gloved finger. Your coral pendant swings under your jacket, heavier than bone. You pull the notebook from your bag and write, slowly, as if each line is a stitch."
    show maya_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "We built a thing to keep our people in place. We opened our hands and the world took what it wanted. I believed openness would be an answer; instead it offered a map others used to redraw coastlines in suitcases."
    "Narration:"
    "You leave the page blank after that last line and close the notebook as if the act could seal a wound. Salt gathers at the corners of your eyes without your permission. There will be letters"
    "from Ilias Navarro, perhaps, and he will send careful photographs and legal edits from airports and conference rooms. Rafi will keep writing. Etta will be where she chooses, and the docks will have a new owner"
    "with a name you don't know."
    "The town shifts its center of gravity; the people you loved scatter in small, dignified departures or stubborn stays. The model we coaxed into life becomes a product in glossy displays. The laboratories and the kits"
    "proliferate in places you never walked. The immediate danger of the ocean has not gone away; the financiers make it easier to measure and harder to feel."
    "You stand until the lamps blur. At last, you open your hand and touch the coral pendant you never let go of. It is carved with a name you say under your breath until the tide takes it and the sound becomes only memory."

    maya_kestrel "We tried to make something that would hold."
    "Narration:"
    "There are days when the bitterness is a near-constant tide, and there are days when you can still feel the quiet rightness of seedlings pressed into mud, the apprentices' laughter, Ilias Navarro's hopeful eyes. Those moments are not erased; they are made complicated."
    "You close your notebook and set it on the bench. The harbor breathes in and out like something that does not need to be convinced to continue."
    "Maya Kestrel [Thought]: This is the cost of trying in a world that monetizes every saving grace. You have particular griefs to carry: Etta's emptied dock, Rafi's ache, Ilias Navarro's distance, the ledger of memos that"
    "show how openness can be weaponized. You catalogue them like a litany to be remembered."
    "Narration:"
    "You do not have a blueprint for undoing what was done. You have, instead, a knowledge of how things break and which broken pieces might still be reclaimed by hands that learned to work in mud."
    "That knowledge is yours to steward. Whether Hearthbend will heed it remains to be seen, but the town continues — imperfect, quiet, stubborn — and you are still here to bear witness."
    hide maya_kestrel

